‘When I got home, the company I work for got in touch and asked if I was free to do some work for Mr Salmond and I was very happy to do it.

‘I’m not doing it for the money – I wanted to make a contribution to Scottish political history.’

Having worked in risky conditions around the world, Mr Sansum said the Scottish referendum had been relatively peaceful.

‘I spent five to six months in Libya with the UN and saw men with AK-47s outside polling stations,’ he said.

‘And polling stations were blown up if they were expected to return the wrong result – so I’m happier dodging eggs than bullets.’

